description: With a known-good 12 V battery now installed, use a multimeter to verify that ~12 V is present across the two output cables of the power supply module. Then, while keeping battery connected, measure voltage at the input pair of cables on Control Module 1 (on the face connected to the PSU). Compare: if 12 V is at the PSU outputs but not at Control Module 1 inputs, suspect a mis-connection or swapped cables between PSU and Control Module 1; if no 12 V at PSU outputs, suspect an internal open or miswired connection in the power supply module itself., outcome='12 V is present between PSU Output Cable (+) and PSU Output Cable (−), and the same ~12 V is present between Control Input Cable (+) 1 and Control Input Cable (−) 1. No polarity inversion is detected between the PSU output cables and Control Module 1 input cables.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=80.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> series chain of control modules 1–8,
description: With the battery installed and all switches set to ON, measure the DC voltage at the input and output cable pairs of each control module in sequence (module 1 through 8). For each module, check that ~12 V appears across its input pair and again across its output pair, and note the first module where the voltage disappears or polarity becomes incorrect., outcome='Modules 1 and 2 show ~12 V across both their input and output cable pairs with correct polarity. At module 3, the output pair voltage drops to ~0 V, and all subsequent modules (3–8) have ~0 V on both input and output pairs; no polarity inversions are indicated in these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=720.0, cost_breakdown=[('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> control module 3 internal switch and LED branch,
description: Open the inspection panel of Control Module 3 (without changing any wiring), keep its switch in the ON position, and with the battery connected measure: (1) continuity of the main series path across the switch terminals; (2) voltage from its input + to input −; (3) voltage from its output + to output −; and (4) continuity directly between input + and output +, and between input − and output −. This will distinguish whether the main series conductors are open inside module 3 (independent of the switch/indicator circuit) or whether the problem is in the switch/LED branch only., outcome='Control Switch 3 itself tests nominal, but the nearby anomaly notes that Control Input Cable (+) 3 has a disconnected floating end that was originally tied to the switch. The positive main path from Control Input Cable (+) 3 to Control Output Cable (+) 3 is open-circuit, while the negative path from Control Input Cable (−) 3 to Control Output Cable (−) 3 shows a low-resistance short with all negative-side voltages near 0 V.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=185.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
